        Wednesday November 24, 2004     </div>

<p>
   <a name="simplifying_acegi_configuration" id="simplifying_acegi_configuration"></a>
   <b class="entryTitle" property="dc:title">Simplifying Acegi Configuration</b> <p>Lately, I've been toying with <a href="http://acegisecurity.sf.net">Acegi</a>.
In case you've not heard yet, Acegi is an excellent security framework
built upon the Spring Framework. Using Acegi you can declaratively
apply security to your applications with little or no change to your
application code. It accomplishes this using servlet filters for web
applications and using Spring's AOP for securing at the method level.</p>

<p>(Note: Incidentally, even though Acegi is built in Spring, your web
application does not have to be Spring-based to use Acegi. Acegi only
needs to be able to intercept requests to your application using
servlet filters.)</p>

<p>I've used Acegi in a number of applications, starting with some
examples for <a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/1932394354">Spring in Action</a>, then in a production
application at my day job. Now I'm using Acegi in a personal project
that I'm working on at home.</p>

<p>Once you've used Acegi in more than one application, you start to
notice that you end up configuring the same &lt;bean&gt; elements, with
very little change, in all of your apps. In fact, in my latest
Acegi-secured application, I found myself copying my Acegi
configuration file and tweaking it slightly.</p>

<p>While the copy-n-paste approach usually works, I began looking for
a better way. The first thing I did was to examine my Acegi
configuration files closely and look for what differed between each
application. More importantly, I made note of what was the same
between each application.</p>

<p>What follows is how I extracted the common configuration between
all of my Acegi-secured applications into a reusable configuration,
leaving me to only configure what is unique. I won't be discussing
Acegi security in detail here. For a more detailed discussion of how
to secure your applications with Acegi, please refer to chapter 11 of
<a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/1932394354">Spring in Action</a>. Also, Matthew Porter has written an
excellent article on Acegi at <a
href="http://www.javalobby.org/articles/acegisecurity/part1.jsp">Javalobby</a>.</p>

<p>First, you should know that I split the configuration of my Spring
beans into several files, one for each layer of the application
(presentation, service, data access, and security). If I'm using
Spring MVC, I let the DispatcherServlet load the presentation-layer
configuration. To load the other configurations, I use Spring's
<code>ContextLoaderListener</code>:</p>

<code>
&lt;context-param&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;param-name&gt;contextConfigLocation&lt;/param-name&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;param-value&gt;/WEB-INF/myapp-service.xml,/WEB-INF/myapp-data-hibernate.xml,
/WEB-INF/myapp-security.xml&lt;/param-value&gt;<br>
&lt;/context-param&gt;<br>
<br>
&lt;listener&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;listener-name&gt;context&lt;/listener-name&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;listener-class&gt;org.springframework.web.context.ContextLoaderListener&lt;/listener-class&gt;<br>
&lt;/listener&gt;
</code>

<p>You may choose to break your application up differently, but this
is how I do it.</p>

<p>The myapp-security.xml file is where I configure Acegi's
beans. This file is no featherweight. In most of my applications, I end up
configuring 15 or more beans here. And, as I have said, the bulk of
the beans configured in this file are identical from one application to the next.</p>

<p>I began looking for what differed between each application. I
found that only 5 out of those 15+ beans were different. And even

then, the differences were often small.</p>

<p>For example, every Acegi-secured web application needs to have a
<code>SecurityEnforcementFilter</code> bean declared. This bean is wired with
references to a <code>FilterSecurityInterceptor</code> and an
<code>AuthenticationEntryPoint</code>--in every app! This bean configuration is
identical across all of my apps</p>

<p>Also, every Acegi-secured web application needs to have an
<code>AuthenticationProcessingFilter</code> bean. Most of the properties of this
bean are configured the same in all of my applications, but the
"authenticationFailureUrl" property may vary from one app to the
next. Must I redeclare this bean in every application, just to change
this one property?</p>

<p>The end to this madness I created a base configuration of Acegi beans, configuring what is common between all of my applications. Then I used the <code>parent</code> attribute of the <code>&lt;bean&gt</code>;
element to "sub-bean" a handful of beans in the base configuration to meet each of my application's specific needs.</p>

<p>To start, I created acegi-common.xml, a Spring configuration
file that declares the Acegi beans and properties that are common to
all of my applications:</p>

<code>
&lt;?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?&gt;<br>
&lt;!DOCTYPE beans PUBLIC "-//SPRING//DTD BEAN//EN" <br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"http://www.springframework.org/dtd/spring-beans.dtd"&gt;<br>
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;!-- = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = =<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; = SECURING AT THE HTTP REQUEST LEVEL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = --&gt;<br>
&lt;beans&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;!-- = = = = = = = SECURITY FILTERS = = = = = = = --&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;bean id="securityEnforcementFilter"<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;class="net.sf.acegisecurity.intercept.web.SecurityEnforcementFilter"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="filterSecurityInterceptor"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;ref bean="filterInvocationInterceptor"/&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/property&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="authenticationEntryPoint"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;ref bean="authenticationEntryPoint"/&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/property&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/bean&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;bean id="baseAuthenticationProcessingFilter"<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;class="net.sf.acegisecurity.ui.webapp.AuthenticationProcessingFilter"<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;lazy-init="true"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="authenticationManager"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;ref bean="authenticationManager"/&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/property&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="filterProcessesUrl"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;value&gt;/j_acegi_security_check&lt;/value&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/property&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="authenticationFailureUrl"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;value&gt;/jsp/loginfailed.jsp&lt;/value&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/property&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="defaultTargetUrl"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;value&gt;/</value&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/property&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/bean&gt;<br>
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;bean id="autoIntegrationFilter"<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;class="net.sf.acegisecurity.ui.AutoIntegrationFilter"/&gt;<br>
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;bean id="baseAuthenticationEntryPoint" class=<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"net.sf.acegisecurity.ui.webapp.AuthenticationProcessingFilterEntryPoint"<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;lazy-init="true"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="loginFormUrl"&gt;&lt;value&gt;/jsp/login.jsp&lt;/value&gt;&lt;/property&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="forceHttps"&gt;&lt;value&gt;false&lt;/value&gt;&lt;/property&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/bean&gt;<br>
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;!-- = = = = = = = = SECURITY INTERCEPTOR = = = = = = = = --&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;bean id="baseFilterInvocationInterceptor"<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;class="net.sf.acegisecurity.intercept.web.FilterSecurityInterceptor"<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;lazy-init="true"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="authenticationManager"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;ref bean="authenticationManager"/&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/property&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="accessDecisionManager"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;ref bean="accessDecisionManager"/&gt; <br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/property&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/bean&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;!-- = = = = = = = = AUTHENTICATION = = = = = = = --&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;bean id="authenticationManager" <br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;class="net.sf.acegisecurity.providers.ProviderManager"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="providers"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;list&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;ref bean="daoAuthenticationProvider"/&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/list&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/property&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/bean&gt;<br>
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;bean id="daoAuthenticationProvider" <br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;class="net.sf.acegisecurity.providers.dao.DaoAuthenticationProvider"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="authenticationDao"&gt;&lt;ref bean="authenticationDao"/&gt;&lt;/property&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/bean&gt;<br>
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;!-- = = = = = = = = ACCESS CONTROL = = = = = = = --&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;bean id="accessDecisionManager" <br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;class="net.sf.acegisecurity.vote.UnanimousBased"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="allowIfAllAbstainDecisions"&gt;&lt;value&gt;false&lt;/value&gt;&lt;/property&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="decisionVoters"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;list&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;ref bean="roleVoter"/&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/list&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/property&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/bean&gt;<br>
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;bean id="roleVoter" class="net.sf.acegisecurity.vote.RoleVoter"/&gt;<br>
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;!-- = = = = = = = = CHANNEL SECURITY = = = = = = = --&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;bean id="baseChannelProcessingFilter" <br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;class="net.sf.acegisecurity.securechannel.ChannelProcessingFilter"<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;lazy-init="true"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="channelDecisionManager"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;ref bean="channelDecisionManager"/&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/property&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/bean&gt;<br>
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;bean id="channelDecisionManager" <br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;class="net.sf.acegisecurity.securechannel.ChannelDecisionManagerImpl"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="channelProcessors"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;list&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;ref bean="secureChannelProcessor"/&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;ref bean="insecureChannelProcessor"/&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/list&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/property&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/bean&gt;<br>
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;bean id="secureChannelProcessor" <br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;class="net.sf.acegisecurity.securechannel.SecureChannelProcessor"/&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;bean id="insecureChannelProcessor" <br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;class="net.sf.acegisecurity.securechannel.InsecureChannelProcessor"/&gt;<br>
&lt;/beans&gt;<br>
</code>

<p>Imagine declaring all of those beans over and over again for each application you write!</p>

<p>The acegi-common.xml file listed above is what I use for all of my Acegi-secured applications. It should be suitable for most web-based applications, but you may find it necessary to tweak it to meet your needs. But any changes you make to acegi-common.xml should be applicable to all of your applications. In a bit, you'll see how to deal with application-specific Acegi configuration.</p>

<p>Notice that on some beans I set <code>lazy-init</code> to "true". That's because
those beans have required properties that I don't want to set until I
get to my app-specific security configuration. <code>lazy-init</code> tells Spring not to try to configure those beans until they are used. Because they'll never be used directly, <code>lazy-init</code> effectively makes those beans abstract, lifting the requirement to wire all of their required properties.</p>

<p>With the base Acegi configuration created, I add acegi-common.xml to the list of Spring
configurations loaded by ContextLoaderListener:</p>

<code>
&lt;context-param&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;param-name&gt;contextConfigLocation&lt;/param-name&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;param-value&gt;/WEB-INF/myapp-service.xml,/WEB-INF/myapp-data-hibernate.xml,
/WEB-INF/myapp-security.xml,<b>/WEB-INF/acegi-common.xml</b>&lt;/param-value&gt;<br>
&lt;/context-param&gt;<br>
<br>
&lt;listener&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;listener-name&gt;context&lt;/listener-name&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;listener-class&gt;org.springframework.web.context.ContextLoaderListener&lt;/listener-class&gt;<br>
&lt;/listener&gt;
</code>


<p>Now I'm able to greatly reduce the complexity of myapp-security.xml
by using the <code>parent</code> attribute of <code>&lt;bean&gt;</code> to create sub-beans of
the beans in acegi-common.xml:</p>

<code>
&lt;beans&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;bean id="authenticationProcessingFilter"<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;parent="baseAuthenticationProcessingFilter"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="authenticationFailureUrl"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;value&gt;/jsp/badlogin.jsp&lt;/value&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/property&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/bean&gt;<br>
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;bean id="authenticationEntryPoint"<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;parent="baseAuthenticationEntryPoint"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="loginFormUrl"&gt;&lt;value&gt;/jsp/login.jsp&lt;/value&gt;&lt;/property&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/bean&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;bean id="filterInvocationInterceptor"<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;parent="baseFilterInvocationInterceptor"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="objectDefinitionSource"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;value&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;CONVERT_URL_TO_LOWERCASE_BEFORE_COMPARISON<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\A/admin/.*\Z=ROLE_ADMIN<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/value&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/property&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/bean&gt;<br>
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;bean id="authenticationDao"<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;class="net.sf.acegisecurity.providers.dao.memory.InMemoryDaoImpl"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="userMap"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;value&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;admin=password,ROLE_ADMIN<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/value&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/property&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/bean&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;bean id="channelProcessingFilter" <br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;parent="baseChannelProcessingFilter"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;property name="filterInvocationDefinitionSource"&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;value&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;CONVERT_URL_TO_LOWERCASE_BEFORE_COMPARISON<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\A/jsp/login.jsp\Z=REQUIRES_SECURE_CHANNEL<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\A/j_acegi_security_check.*\Z=REQUIRES_SECURE_CHANNEL<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\A.*\Z=REQUIRES_INSECURE_CHANNEL<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/value&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/property&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/bean&gt;<br>
&lt;/beans&gt;
</code>

<p>Now my application-specific Acegi configuration is made up of only
5 beans. Four of them are sub-beans of Acegi beans declared in
acegi-common.xml.</p>

<p>The other is "authenticationDao" which is
fully-declared here because it will vary between
applications. Here I'm using <code>InMemoryDaoImpl</code>, but I'd probably choose to use a more
production-worthy implementation such as <code>PasswordAuthenticationDao</code> in most of my applications.</p>

<p>Furthermore, the "channelProcessingFilter" bean is
optional and may not be needed in all applications. If you don't need
it, the application-specific configuration can be reduced to only 4
beans.</p>

<p>All I need to do to reuse acegi-common.xml in all of my
applications is to ensure that it is placed in the "/WEB-INF"
directory.</p>

<p>Optionally, I can carry it around in a JAR file. Just create a JAR
file with acegi-common.xml in the root of the JAR, place it in the
"/WEB-INF/lib" directory, and make a slight change to how
<code>ContextLoaderListener</code> is loaded:

<code>
&lt;context-param&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;param-name&gt;contextConfigLocation&lt;/param-name&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;param-value&gt;/WEB-INF/myapp-service.xml,/WEB-INF/myapp-data-hibernate.xml,
/WEB-INF/myapp-security.xml,<b>classpath:acegi-common.xml</b>&lt;/param-value&gt;<br>
&lt;/context-param&gt;<br>
<br>
&lt;listener&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;listener-name&gt;context&lt;/listener-name&gt;<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;listener-class&gt;org.springframework.web.context.ContextLoaderListener&lt;/listener-class&gt;<br>
&lt;/listener&gt;
</code>

<p>As simple as acegi-common.xml is right now, it doesn't matter much
if I package it in a JAR or not. But if I end up writing some reusable Acegi
components (perhaps my own voter class), then the JAR file makes more
sense as I can package the acegi-common.xml along with any custom
classes it needs.</p>

<p>Even with a simple acegi-common.xml file, the JAR
file approach may be appealing to those of you who use Maven, as you
can place the JAR in a shared repository and declare it as a
dependency in all of your apps.</p>
   <span class="dateStamp">(2004-11-24 16:58:07.0)</span>
